inputDescriptors.description:
Allows the SVN client to accept self-signed SSL server certificates without installing them into the Azure DevOps service role and/or Build Agent computers.

Same as the `--trust-server-cert` option of the `svn` command line utility.
inputDescriptors.name: Accept untrusted SSL certificates

inputDescriptors.description:
If you use multiple credentials in a build pipeline to download a complete set of the source from Subversion, you should specify the `Realm name` in each of them. The `Realm name` represents a sort of "authentication namespace" used by the Subversion repository to select the appropriate Subversion identity database. Along with the repository server's schema, hostname, and port it forms a key that the build agent uses to select the specific credential from the set provided in the build pipeline.

To find out the `Realm name`, you could do any of the following:
  • If you access the repository via `HTTP` or `HTTPS`: Open the repo in a web browser without saved credentials. It will use the `Realm Name` in the authentication dialog.
  • Use the command line `svn` program. If you don't have stored the credentials, run e.g. `svn info https://svnserver/repo`. You will see the `Realm name` when it asks you to enter a password.
  • If you have already stored the credentials to access the repository, look for the `Realm name` in one of the files in the Subversion authentication cache section of your user profile, e.g. in `~/.subversion/auth/svn/simple` or `C:\Users\yourname\Application Data\Subversion\auth\svn.simple`.
inputDescriptors.name: Realm name

url.helpText:
If you use this authentication credential as a main Subversion repository service connection, you should specify the full repository URL, e.g. `https://svnserver/repo` or `svn://svnserver:3690/repositories/myrepo`. The `Realm name` parameter is optional in this case.

If you use this authentication credential as an additional service connection for Subversion externals, you may specify the schema, hostname, and port only, e.g. `https://svnserver:443` or `svn://svnserver:3690`. The `Realm name` parameter is required in this case.

This is the path inside the container where the build artifacts are uploaded from Jenkins. This assumes that each build is uploaded inside a separate folder under Common Virtual Path having the `${BUILD_NUMBER}` as the folder name.

**Examples**:

To upload each build inside the container root, the Jenkins Post Build action should have the value as `${BUILD_NUMBER}` and this field should be set to empty.

If you want each build to go inside a folder say `drops/builds/`, the Jenkins Post Build action should have the value as `drops/builds/${BUILD_NUMBER}` and this field should be set to `drops/builds/`.

inputs.email-subject: A project you are a member of has been renamed

footer.content: This is a mandatory service communication.

hero.message: The team project {{ event.previousName }} has been renamed to {{ event.currentName }} in the {{#isHosted}}organization{{else}}collection{{/isHosted}} {{ event.collectionName }}.{{#unless event.notifyAllUsers}} We noticed the team project contains a large number of valid users. Instead of notifying all of them we have chosen to send this email to the collection and project administrators so they can share this information with the appropriate set of impacted users.{{/unless}}
hero.title: Your team project was renamed!

inputs.summary: The team project {{ event.previousName }} has been renamed to {{ event.currentName }} in the {{#isHosted}}organization{{else}}collection{{/isHosted}} {{ event.collectionName }}

contributions.description: Template that renders the what to expect section of the rename email

inputs.gitMessage: If the team project uses Git, then update your remote to use the new project name.
inputs.mainMessage: The team projects version control paths, work items, build pipelines, and other artifacts have been updated to reflect the new name. {{#if event.notifyAllUsers}}Depending on how you work with the team project, you may need to take additional actions:{{else}}We recommend notifying users who work with the team project frequently that it has been renamed and including the following actions they may need to take:{{/if}}
inputs.tfvcMessage: If the team project uses TFVC, update your Visual Studio client to the latest release or update, and perform a get to update your workspaces with the new project name.
inputs.vsMessage: If you use Visual Studio, Eclipse, Microsoft Excel, PowerPoint, or Project with the {{ @root.system.productName }} team project, save your work and restart each application.

properties.description: Projects locked due to a violation of terms of service subscription

footer.content: This is a mandatory service communication.

hero.message: All content in violation of the {{ @root.system.productName }} code of conduct will need to be removed before you can make your projects public again. Reach out to customer support to get unblocked.
hero.preMessage: Image and/or video content was found in your {{ @root.system.productName }} organization {{ event.collectionUrl }}{{#if event.projectName }}, under the project {{ event.projectName }},{{/if}} that violates our code of conduct. As a result, all projects in your organization have been set back to private. Members of the organization are still able to access projects, but no projects will be publicly visible.
